Compile and run your application in your IDE or your shell.**Input:**```shell
javac CreateIndex.java
java CreateIndex
```**Output:**```
New index name: default
```The MongoDB Search `date` type takes the following parameter:| Option | Type   | Necessity | Description                                                               |
| ------ | ------ | --------- | ------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| type   | string | required  | Human-readable label that identifies this field type. Value must be date. |The following index definition examples use collections in the
[sample data sets](available-sample-datasets). After you
[Load Sample Data Into Atlas](load-sample-data), you can use
these examples to index fields as the dateFacet type.Basic ExampleThe following example index definition indexes the  `released`
field as the MongoDB Search `date` type to support queries against that
field using MongoDB Search operators such as [near](near-ref),
[range](range-ref), and [equals](equals-ref).```java
import com.mongodb.client.MongoClient;
import com.mongodb.client.MongoClients;
import com.mongodb.client.MongoCollection;
import com.mongodb.client.MongoDatabase;
import org.bson.Document;

public class CreateIndex {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // connect to your Atlas cluster
        String uri = "<connection-string>";

        try (MongoClient mongoClient = MongoClients.create(uri)) {
            // set namespace
            MongoDatabase database = mongoClient.getDatabase("sample_mflix");
            MongoCollection<Document> collection = database.getCollection("movies");

            Document index = new Document("mappings",
                    new Document("dynamic", false)
                        .append("fields", new Document("released", 
                                              new Document("type", "date"))));

            String result = collection.createSearchIndex(index);
            System.out.println("New index name: " + result);
        }
    }
}
```Multiple Types ExampleThe following example index definition indexes the  `released`
field as the `date` and `dateFacet` types to return the
following types of results for your queries:* Search results for queries using MongoDB Search operators like
  [near](near-ref), [equals](equals-ref), and [range](range-ref).

* Metadata results for queries using MongoDB Search [faceted navigation](fts-facet-ref).```java
import com.mongodb.client.MongoClient;
import com.mongodb.client.MongoClients;
import com.mongodb.client.MongoCollection;
import com.mongodb.client.MongoDatabase;
import java.util.Arrays;
import org.bson.Document;

public class CreateIndex {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // connect to your Atlas cluster
        String uri = "<connection-string>";

        try (MongoClient mongoClient = MongoClients.create(uri)) {
            // set namespace
            MongoDatabase database = mongoClient.getDatabase("sample_mflix");
            MongoCollection<Document> collection = database.getCollection("movies");

            Document dateType = new Document("type", "date");
            Document dateFacetType = new Document("type", "dateFacet");

            Document index = new Document("mappings",
                    new Document("dynamic", false)
                        .append("fields", new Document("released", 
                                Arrays.asList(dateType, dateFacetType))));

            String result = collection.createSearchIndex(index);
            System.out.println("New index name: " + result);
        }
    }
}
```To learn how to set up and run the following example code, see
Define the Index for the token Type.You can use the MongoDB Search `date` type to index date values. You can query
fields of type `date` using the MongoDB Search [range](range-ref),
[near](near-ref), [in](in-ref), and [equals](equals-ref) operators. You can
also run a [faceted navigation](fts-facet-ref) query on `date` type fields.You can also use the `date` type to index:- Fields whose value is an array of dates. To learn more, see
  [How to Index the Elements of an Array](fts-array-ref).

- Date fields inside an array of documents indexed as the
  [embeddedDocuments](bson-data-types-embedded-documents) type.

- Date fields for sorting. MongoDB Search automatically indexes all date fields
  in indexes created after [July 2023](fts20230710) for
  [sorting](sort-ref) the MongoDB Search results. For preexisting indexes,
  you must rebuild the index to use date fields in the index for
  sorting. To learn more, see [index update](fts-index-rebuild) and
  [sorting](sort-ref).> **Note:** To query indexed date values inside arrays, you must use the [range](range-ref)
> operator. You can't use the [near](near-ref) operator
> to query date values stored in an array, even if you have a MongoDB Search
> index on the date values inside the array.If you enable [dynamic mappings](static-dynamic-mappings), MongoDB Search
automatically indexes fields of type dateFacet. You can
use the **Visual Editor** or the  **JSON Editor** in the Atlas UI to
index fields as the dateFacet type.

